  "name": "Riftweasel",
  "pfs": {
    "availability": "Standard",
    "subtype": "pfs",
    "type": "stat_block_section"
  },
  "schema_version": 1.4,
  "sections": [
    {
      "name": "Riftweasel",
      "sections": [
        {
          "image": {
            "image": "Sidebar_2_AdditionalLore.png",
            "name": "Additional Lore",
            "type": "image"
          },
          "name": "Sadistic Scavengers",
          "sidebar_heading": "Additional Lore",
          "sidebar_type": "additional_lore",
          "sources": [
            {
              "link": {
                "alt": "Pathfinder #212: A Voice in the Blight pg. 87",
                "aonid": 255,
                "game-obj": "Sources",
                "name": "Pathfinder #212: A Voice in the Blight pg. 87",
                "type": "link"
              },
              "name": "Pathfinder #212: A Voice in the Blight",
              "page": 87,
              "type": "source"
            }
          ],
          "subtype": "sidebar",
          "text": "As a scavenger, the riftweasel is rather intelligent, though it also finds great delight in tormenting creatures. It won't hesitate to arrange victims in unpleasant tableaus, and particularly enjoys feeding on paralyzed creatures, eating parts of the body that won't quickly kill. Once a victim dies, they enjoy using talking corpse to mock and interrogate their meals as they finish them. Those subjected to a vision of death by a rift weasel typically see themselves eaten and mocked after death by the cruel creature.",
          "type": "section"
        }
      ],
      "sources": [
        {
          "link": {
            "alt": "Pathfinder #212: A Voice in the Blight pg. 87",
            "aonid": 255,
            "game-obj": "Sources",
            "name": "Pathfinder #212: A Voice in the Blight pg. 87",
            "type": "link"
          },
          "name": "Pathfinder #212: A Voice in the Blight",
          "page": 87,
          "type": "source"
        }
      ],
      "text": "Riftweasels have long, thin tendrils along their snouts that function like whiskers in sensing movement; these grant riftweasels the precise tremorsense to pinpoint delicious grubs and other scavengers while they hide inside of larger corpses.",
      "type": "section"
    }
  ],
  "sources": [
    {
